Class CloneableObject

java.lang.Object
  nitf.NITFObject
      nitf.DestructibleObject
          nitf.CloneableObject
Direct Known Subclasses:
Record
public abstract class CloneableObject
extends DestructibleObject

This class is a NITFObject that can be cloned.

-------------------------- Note to Developer -------------------------- Since this extends DestructibleObject, when it gets created, it is referenced within the NITFUtil class. When we clone things, we want a separate reference to that new memory. Since DestructibleObject takes care of that for us, we don't need anything separate in here that tracks the clone memory.

For some objects that we may want to make cloneable from within Java, we may not want to destruct the memory of the original, since it might be part of a larger structure (for example, FileHeader is part of a Record, and should not be destructed or else it will disrupct the parent Record). However, we will want to be able to destruct the clone object. For this reason, these particular objects will have to check to see if itself is a clone first before calling the super.destruct(). Thus, for some objects, it is a good idea to override the DestructibleObject.destruct() method. Keep that in mind.
